<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Thomson, John. Journal, Mackenzie River, 1800-1802. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0021</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">danger of its breaking in Pieces<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  M<sup>r</sup> Porter &amp; John departed from us in the afternoon, the former left us Bernier to help S<sup>t</sup> Cir<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Thursday the 2<sup>d</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Rained a little, decamped after daylight<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Bernier refused to embark in S<sup>t</sup> Cirs Canoe, but made him put once ashore to gum.  Encamped after Dark<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Friday the 3<sup>d</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Very Strong head Wind accompanied with Hail &amp; Snow<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Wind bound all the afternoon our canoes are so weakly Manned that we could not possiblely advc<sup>e</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Saturday the 4<sup>th</sup><span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  About Midnight set off &amp; a little before sunset arrived at the Slave Lake Fort<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  M<sup>r</sup> Porter &amp; all his people arrived early this morning<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  S<sup>t</sup> Cirs Canoe is so very bad that the Third Man is constanly employed throwing out the water, therefore I was very much afraid that if we attempted hazarding ourselves with it in the Slave Lake, we would be in great danger of being overtaken by the Ice<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  Consequently rather then run that Risk, we prevailled upon Mandeville &amp; Noiseau  to sell us their Canoe for 150 Livres <span class="AddHand-author">in goods</span> &amp; S<sup>t</sup> Cirs Canoe &amp; <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Boat</span> &#8211; the wood of the latter is all of Cedar &amp; when made a new will be full as good a Canoe as the others.  We without doubt will be deemed very extravagant but it really was a case of necessity &#8211; but to avoid as much as we can the former imputations M<sup>r</sup> Wentzel &amp; myself have agreed to pay the odd 50 Livres between us<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span>  M<sup>r</sup> Porter gave us 6 orignal quarters, 2 Placcotés, 1 Blader Grease<span class="AddHand-editors">[,]</span> 16 quarts Salt &amp; 77 Sinews to make hare snares &amp;<sup>c</sup> &#8211; he also allowed us to take 2 of his Men in order to help us over the Lake &#8211; that is Bernier &amp; Laviolette &#8211; the latter I have taken with a winter lion keep &amp; send out some other in his place in order that he may take charge of Post in the Summer as none of the others are fit for that purpose<span class="AddHand-editors">[.]</span></p>

<p align="page-number"><span class="AddHand-editors">[2]</span></p>

